\textbf{Key Insight:}
Minimum modulo $|23|$ is attained when the difference between two numbers is minimal.

\textbf{Derivation:}
Since $20a - 23b \equiv 20a \pmod{23}$, we have that $I(a, b)$ is minimal if and only if $20a \leqslant 23b$, or equivalently, $a \leqslant \frac{23}{20}b$. Since $a$ and $b$ are natural numbers, it follows that $a \leqslant \lfloor \frac{23}{20}b \rfloor$. Now, since $\lfloor \frac{23}{20}b \rfloor \leqslant \frac{23}{20}b < \frac{23}{20}(b+1)$, it follows that $I(a, b) \geqslant I(\lfloor \frac{23}{20}b \rfloor, b)$. On the other hand, for any $c \in \mathbb{N}$, we have that $I(c, b) \geqslant I(c, \lceil \frac{23}{20}b \rceil) \geqslant I(\lfloor \frac{23}{20}b \rfloor, \lceil \frac{23}{20}b \rceil) \geqslant I(\lfloor \frac{23}{20}b \rfloor, b)$. Therefore, $I(a, b) = I(\lfloor \frac{23}{20}b \rfloor, b)$.

\textbf{Conclusion:}
The minimum value of $I(a, b)$ is equal to $I(\lfloor \frac{23}{20}b \rfloor, b)$.

\textbf{Verification:}
For example, if $b = 1$, then $I(a, 1) = |20a - 23| \geqslant |20 \cdot \lfloor \frac{23}{20} \rfloor - 23| = 0$, while if $a = \lfloor \frac{23}{20} \rfloor = 1$, then $I(1, 1) = |20 - 23| = 3$.

